                <exercise workspace="4in">
                    <title>Observations: Modular Arithmetic</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        Every element has an <term>additive inverse</term>. For example,
                                        <m>2+1 \equiv 0 (\mod 3)</m> and <m>2+2 \equiv 0 (\mod 4)</m>.
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        In <m>\Z / 3\Z</m>, every non-zero element also has a
                                        <term>multiplicative inverse</term>. For example, <m>2 \cdot 2 \equiv 1 (\mod 3)</m>.
                            
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        In <m>\Z / 4\Z</m>, multiplication is strange. For example,
                                        <m>2x \equiv 1 (\mod 4)</m> has no solution, and <m>2 \cdot 2 \equiv 0 (\mod 4)</m>, 
                                        even though <m>2</m> is non-zero!
                                        
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        A helpful fact is that <m>\overline{a}</m> has a multiplicative inverse in 
                                        <m>\Z / m\Z</m> if and only if the greatest common divisor of <m>a</m> and <m>m</m>
                                        is <m>1</m>. This makes <m>\Z / p\Z</m>, for <m>p</m> prime, special!
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                </exercise>
